  "prompt": "What's the weightage given to 10th, 12th and graduation marks in IIM's selection process?",
  "response": "In the IIM (Indian Institutes of Management) selection process, candidates are evaluated based on multiple criteria. Here's a general breakdown of the weightage for academic marks:\n\n1. CAT (Common Admission Test) Score: \n- Typically carries the highest weightage (around 50-60%)\n\n2. Academic Performance:\n- 10th Standard Marks: Around 5-10%\n- 12th Standard Marks: Around 10-15%\n- Graduation Marks: Around 10-15%\n\n3. Work Experience (for those with prior work experience):\n- Can contribute around 10-20% of the total selection weight\n\n4. Personal Interview and Written Ability Test (WAT):\n- Around 10-20% of the total evaluation\n\nPlease note that the exact weightage can vary slightly among different IIMs and may change from year to year. The precise percentages are not publicly disclosed and can differ based on the specific admission cycle.\n\nThe most critical factor remains the CAT score, followed by academic performance and other parameters like work experience and interview performance.\n\nFor the most accurate and current information, it's best to check the official websites of specific IIMs or consult their admission brochures.",
